}},"excerpt":"Snag all nine on sale for less than $35.","show_sponsorship":null,"sponsorship_footer":null,"channel":"Culture","channel_label":"Culture","channel_link":"https://mashable.com/Culture/","tweet_text":"Learn how to succeed in digital marketing with these online classes"},{"_id":"5f29caac0557810083000008","id":"/article/google-plus-settlement/","title":"Google might owe you $12","title_tag":null,"author":"Jack Morse","post_date":"2020-08-04T20:52:56+00:00","post_date_rfc":"Tue, 04 Aug 2020 20:52:56 +0000","formatted_date":"08/04/2020","sort_key":"1K3809","link":"https://mashable.com/article/google-plus-settlement/","content":{"plain":"{\"player\":{\"description\":\"A little goes a long way.\",\"image\":\"https://mondrian.mashable.com/uploads%252Fvideo_uploaders%252Fdistribution_thumb%252Fimage%252F90105%252F26784700-fc76-4de5-aa35-ec686979602c.jpg%252F930x520.jpg?signature=3BftVLxrrJJ-G11zbmhMsSuDckQ=&source=https%3A%2F%2Fblueprint-api-production.s3.amazonaws.com\",\"mediaid\":\"360OeJxglV\",\"preload\":false,\"title\":\"It's surprisingly easy to be more secure online — Clarification Please\",\"sources\":[{\"file\":\"https://vdist.aws.mashable.com/cms/2019/1/92a4304e-5503-7b98/hls.m3u8\"},{\"file\":\"https://vdist.aws.mashable.com/cms/2019/1/92a4304e-5503-7b98/dash.mpd\"},{\"file\":\"https://vdist.aws.mashable.com/cms/2019/1/92a4304e-5503-7b98/mp4/1080.mp4\"},{\"file\":\"https://vdist.aws.mashable.com/cms/2019/1/92a4304e-5503-7b98/mp4/720.mp4\"},{\"file\":\"https://vdist.aws.mashable.com/cms/2019/1/92a4304e-5503-7b98/mp4/480.mp4\"}],\"player_id\":\"WmgvXppl\"},\"options\":{\"disableAds\":false,\"disableSharing\":false,\"nextupAction\":\"autoplay\",\"embedUrl\":\"https://mashable.com/videos/blueprint:360OeJxglV/embed/?player=offsite\",\"standaloneUrl\":null,\"post\":{\"url\":\"https://mashable.com/article/google-chrome-83-update/\",\"date\":\"2020-05-19T20:51:01.862Z\",\"bp_id\":114840,\"wp_id\":null}},\"advertising\":{\"params\":{\"keywords\":\"tech,mashable-video,cybersecurity,malware,how to,password,vpn,antivirus,authentication,clarification-please\",\"sec0\":null,\"sec1\":\"\",\"prc\":\"\"}},\"analytics\":{\"labels\":\"tech,mashable-video,cybersecurity,malware,how to,password,vpn,antivirus,authentication,clarification-please\",\"videoSeriesName\":null}}It only took nine years, but Google+ may finally be worth something to users. Specifically, up to $12. \nPast users of the now-defunct social media platform were hipped to a potential windfall Tuesday morning by an ominous looking email that helpfully assured wary recipients: \"You are not being sued.\" At issue is at least one \"bug\" which revealed non-public user data to third-party developers, and a resulting class-action lawsuit. \nAccording to the litigation website, you may qualify for a piece of the $7.5 million settlement if you are in the U.S., had a consumer Google+ account between January 1, 2015 and April 2, 2019, and had your \"non-public Profile Information exposed as a result of the software bugs Google announced on October 8, 2018 and December 10, 2018.\"\nYou have until Oct. 8, 2020, to file, and can do so here. \nNow, as is often the case with these things (remember Equifax?), there are a few important caveats. For starters, whether or not you get 12 whole dollars depends on how many people file a claim. As the the settlement info page explains, $12 is the maximum amount you may receive. You might just get pennies.\nSEE ALSO: Google to kill Google+ early after exposing personal data of more than 50 million\nAlso, the settlement needs to get final approval by the courts. That decision will be made on Nov. 19, but as it has already been granted preliminary approval, it should (theoretically) be approved with little fuss. \nSo fill out your claim, maybe get your $12, and then happily forget you ever willingly handed over your personal data to Google+ in the first place. "},"image":"https://mondrian.mashable.com/uploads%252Fstory%252Fthumbnail%252F117731%252Fd370b298-3afe-492d-a62e-08c0c43b55b1.jpg%252F950x534__filters%253Aquality%252880%2529.jpg?signature=6gyu7fXQMS4zhY1_yYGZ2K-ZoqY=&source=https%3A%2F%2Fblueprint-api-production.s3.amazonaws.com","feature_image":"https://mondrian.mashable.com/uploads%252Fstory%252Fthumbnail%252F117731%252Fd370b298-3afe-492d-a62e-08c0c43b55b1.jpg%252F1438x0.jpg?signature=RYCtlWWwmmYBPTW36pD0X_kcMk8=&source=https%3A%2F%2Fblueprint-api-production.s3.amazonaws.com","responsive_images":[{"image":"https://mondrian.mashable.com/uploads%252Fstory%252Fthumbnail%252F117731%252Fd370b298-3afe-492d-a62e-08c0c43b55b1.jpg%252F356x205.jpg?signature=NYa8X39mbF04CmsG3ujAPeXZ-DQ=&source=https%3A%2F%2Fblueprint-api-production.s3.amazonaws.com","query":true,"size":"356x205#"},{"image":"https://mondrian.mashable.com/uploads%252Fstory%252Fthumbnail%252F117731%252Fd370b298-3afe-492d-a62e-08c0c43b55b1.jpg%252F712x410.jpg?signature=XXzykT_Z_ogg-9agiUiftGv57SA=&source=https%3A%2F%2Fblueprint-api-production.s3.amazonaws.com","query":"(min-resolution: 1.5dppx)","size":"712x410#"},{"image":"https://mondrian.mashable.com/uploads%252Fstory%252Fthumbnail%252F117731%252Fd370b298-3afe-492d-a62e-08c0c43b55b1.jpg%252F280x157.jpg?signature=Gl-RCpb3AFtsvXO0PE5DPqj9W2M=&source=https%3A%2F%2Fblueprint-api-production.s3.amazonaws.com","query":"(max-width: 480px)","size":"280x157#"},{"image":"https://mondrian.mashable.com/uploads%252Fstory%252Fthumbnail%252F117731%252Fd370b298-3afe-492d-a62e-08c0c43b55b1.jpg%252F560x314.jpg?signature=S99WRhJV-PN9DeKKXfQEFGQQgZw=&source=https%3A%2F%2Fblueprint-api-production.s3.amazonaws.com","query":"(max-width: 480px) and (min-resolution: 1.5dppx)","size":"560x314#"}],"responsive_images_html5":{"img_set_info":{"tag_attributes":{"alt":"Google+ finally good for something: Getting you $12 (maybe)","src":"https://mondrian.mashable.com/uploads%252Fstory%252Fthumbnail%252F117731%252Fd370b298-3afe-492d-a62e-08c0c43b55b1.jpg%252F356x205.jpg?signature=NYa8X39mbF04CmsG3ujAPeXZ-DQ=\u0026source=https%3A%2F%2Fblueprint-api-production.s3.amazonaws.com","src_type":"jpg","loading":"lazy","version_webp_srcset":"https://mondrian.mashable.com/uploads%252Fstory%252Fthumbnail%252F117731%252Fd370b298-3afe-492d-a62e-08c0c43b55b1.webp%252F280x157.webp?signature=5GDF_4sBlEscOPWZAg7jeWVVv2Q=\u0026source=https%3A%2F%2Fblueprint-api-production.s3.amazonaws.com 280w,https://mondrian.mashable.com/uploads%252Fstory%252Fthumbnail%252F117731%252Fd370b298-3afe-492d-a62e-08c0c43b55b1.webp%252F356x205.webp?signature=QXRH6Bqn09DrcN8sLm7CykolEZ0=\u0026source=https%3A%2F%2Fblueprint-api-production.s3.amazonaws.com 356w","naturalWidth":"356","srcset":"https://mondrian.mashable.com/uploads%252Fstory%252Fthumbnail%252F117731%252Fd370b298-3afe-492d-a62e-08c0c43b55b1.jpg%252F280x157.jpg?signature=Gl-RCpb3AFtsvXO0PE5DPqj9W2M=\u0026source=https%3A%2F%2Fblueprint-api-production.s3.amazonaws.com 280w,https://mondrian.mashable.com/uploads%252Fstory%252Fthumbnail%252F117731%252Fd370b298-3afe-492d-a62e-08c0c43b55b1.jpg%252F356x205.jpg?signature=NYa8X39mbF04CmsG3ujAPeXZ-DQ=\u0026source=https%3A%2F%2Fblueprint-api-production.s3.amazonaws.com 356w","sizes":"(max-width: 480px) 280w,356w"}},"image_caption_info":null,"image_credit_info":null,"data_clickthrough_info":null,"version_webp_callback":{}},"display_title":"Google+ finally good for something: Getting you $12 (maybe)","choice":false,"mash_debut":false,"weed_in_america":false,"spotlight":false,"shortcode_data":{"gallery":[],"giftguide":{}},"excerpt":"If Google+ exposed your personal data, you have until Oct. 8 to file a claim. ","show_sponsorship":null,"sponsorship_footer":null,"channel":"Tech","channel_label":"Tech","channel_link":"https://mashable.com/Tech/","tweet_text":"Google might owe you $12"},{"_id":"5f28b529ffba850054000001","id":"/article/twitter-ftc-investigation-fines-250-million-2fa-advertising/","title":"Twitter may have to pay hundreds of millions in fines for privacy screw-up","title_tag":null,"author":"Jack Morse","post_date":"2020-08-04T01:08:56+00:00","post_date_rfc":"Tue, 04 Aug 2020 01:08:56 +0000","formatted_date":"08/04/2020","sort_key":"1K2Xkc","link":"https://mashable.com/article/twitter-ftc-investigation-fines-250-million-2fa-advertising/","content":{"plain":"As far as mistakes go, Twitter's notorious two-factor authentication boondoggle could end being a costly one. \nBuried deep inside the company's Monday 10Q filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission is a note that the social media giant might end up on the receiving end of up to $250 million in fines. At issue was Twitter \"inadvertently\" (it swears) using users' phone numbers for advertising from 2013 to 2019 — numbers that were only provided for security purposes. The Federal Trade Commission apparently didn't take kindly to that, and sent a draft complaint Twitter's way on July 28.\nFor those blessed to not remember every single Twitter privacy scandal, it's worth a reminder just how problematic the 2019 revelation that Twitter matched some users to advertisers' marketing lists based on their 2FA numbers actually was. \nSpecifically, privacy experts noted that using phone numbers volunteered for security reasons for advertising represents a fundamental betrayal of trust. And that betrayal comes with real consequences.  \n\"Twitter 'unintentionally' used the information it got from you to secure your account in order to make money,\" Eva Galperin, the EFF's director of cybersecurity, wrote at the time. \"This kind of behavior undermines people's willingness to use 2FA and makes them less secure in the long run.\"\nIt also, according to Twitter's Monday filing, might just so happen to violate the company's 2011 FTC consent order. \n\"In March 2011, to resolve an investigation into various incidents, we entered into a consent order with the FTC that, among other things, required us to establish an information security program designed to protect non-public consumer information and also requires that we obtain biennial independent security assessments,\" reads the 10Q filing. \"[On] July 28, 2020, we received a draft complaint from the FTC alleging violations of the 2011 consent order with the FTC and the FTC Act.\" \nSEE ALSO: Not even Jack Dorsey can figure out how to use Periscope\nTwitter says the matter \"remains unresolved,\" and estimates the \"probable loss in this matter is $150.0 million to $250.0 million.\"\nWhether such a fine would be enough to prevent similar privacy mistakes in the future is anyone's guess, but it would at least be a start. \nWATCH: It's surprisingly easy to be more secure online"},"image":"https://mondrian.mashable.com/uploads%252Fcard%252Fimage%252F1434008%252F22a55e85-8fd5-40d8-8843-de45e84342c7.jpg%252F950x534__filters%253Aquality%252880%2529.jpg?signature=XzfVFGoidwKRln2lt4PKsDrGjBk=&source=https%3A%2F%2Fblueprint-api-production.s3.amazonaws.com","feature_image":"https://mondrian.mashable.com/uploads%252Fstory%252Fthumbnail%252F117694%252F6740aec0-d399-49a3-adf7-efa31757c638.jpg%252F1438x0.jpg?signature=yA2xSLFb9w7p4Lto4G6d7dk5uRI=&source=https%3A%2F%2Fblueprint-api-production.s3.amazonaws.com","responsive_images":[{"image":"https://mondrian.mashable.com/uploads%252Fstory%252Fthumbnail%252F117694%252F6740aec0-d399-49a3-adf7-efa31757c638.jpg%252F356x205.jpg?signature=Rkq7bYh_FfvxqFnxa227CzYMYv4=&source=https%3A%2F%2Fblueprint-api-production.s3.amazonaws.com","query":true,"size":"356x205#"},{"image":"https://mondrian.mashable.com/uploads%252Fstory%252Fthumbnail%252F117694%252F6740aec0-d399-49a3-adf7-efa31757c638.jpg%252F712x410.jpg?signature=uKdtr_4kZVdF9a9RH0LoZnn0rpU=&source=https%3A%2F%2Fblueprint-api-production.s3.amazonaws.com","query":"(min-resolution: 1.5dppx)","size":"712x410#"},{"image":"https://mondrian.mashable.com/uploads%252Fstory%252Fthumbnail%252F117694%252F6740aec0-d399-49a3-adf7-efa31757c638.jpg%252F280x157.jpg?signature=fXyZG9EVogCkpBkQJPUipdlza9w=&source=https%3A%2F%2Fblueprint-api-production.s3.amazonaws.com","query":"(max-wi